TextArea((24.0, 557.0), (349.0, 418.0)) {'type': 'BROWN'}
  [
    u'GORDON BROWN: ' FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {'grabright': 300, 'type': 'BROWN'}
    u'Net immigration is falling as a result of the measures we are taking. The points system is the ' FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u"key to this. It's done in Australia and other countries. You can't come in unless you've got a " FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u"skill to offer, if you're from outside the European Union. That has meant there are no unskilled " FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u'workers coming into this country, a reduction in skilled workers, a reduction in university ' FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u"students as well. That is what we are actually doing now. We're counting people in and out " FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u'from the end of the year.  ' FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
TextArea((24.0, 563.0), (430.0, 487.0)) {'type': 'CAMERON'}
  [
    u'DAVID CAMERON: ' FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {'grabright': 300, 'type': 'CAMERON'}
    u"I don't want to bore people with the figures, but it is important. Up until 1997, the highest " FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u'number for net migration into the UK was 77,000 in a year. Since 1997, since Labour came to ' FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u"power, it has never been lower than 140,000, sometimes it has been 200,000, that's equivalent " FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u"to two million across a decade. That's just too high, it can be brought down, we have done it in " FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u'the past and can do it again.  ' FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
TextArea((24.0, 550.0), (499.0, 556.0)) {'type': 'BROWN'}
  [
    u'GORDON BROWN: ' FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {'grabright': 300, 'type': 'BROWN'}
    u'What happens is there are a million people from Britain who are in the European Union, and ' FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u'staying in homes and staying in countries of the European Union. And there are one million ' FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u'people from the European Union who are in our country, that is what being part of the ' FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u'European Union is about. There are many British citizens who want the chance to stay for a ' FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u'period of time in other countries in the European Union.  ' FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
TextArea((24.0, 561.0), (568.0, 613.0)) {'type': 'INTERVIEWER'}
  [
    u'ADAM BOULTON: ' FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {'grabright': 300, 'type': 'INTERVIEWER'}
    u" We are going to have to leave it there, I'm afraid that is the end of our audience questions. It's " FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u'now time for the leaders to make their big pitches for your votes. With their closing statements. ' FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u'A reminder that each leader has one-and-a-half minutes for this. Lots were drawn for the order ' FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u'in which they are going to go, we start now with Gordon Brown.  ' FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
TextArea((24.0, 563.0), (625.0, 763.0)) {'type': 'BROWN'}
  [
    u'GORDON BROWN: ' FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {'grabright': 300, 'type': 'BROWN'}
    u"The buck stops here, if you are in the job I'm in, you've got to take responsibility for the " FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u"decisions. We've talked this evening about Afghanistan and the responsibility I take, every day, " FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u'making sure our forces can do the job in Afghanistan, and can soon, as a result of the efforts ' FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u"we are making, bring our forces home. We've talked today also about security, and how we " FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u'need to be part of multilateral disarmament negotiations, so that we, Britain, do not give up our ' FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u'weapons, unless others are prepared to do so, and reduce their weapons as well. We have ' FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u"talked also about the economy this evening, I've heard a number of people ask questions " FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u'about the deficit, ask questions about how the economy is going to fare as businesses in the ' FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u"future, whether in or out of Europe. The issue for me is don't do anything that puts this " FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u'economic recovery at risk. We have fought so hard, for so long, over these last two years, to ' FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u'make sure we get through what has been the worst global financial recession since the 1930s. ' FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u"We've had to take ownership of our banks, we've had call the world together in London to have " FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
TextArea((141.0, 563.0), (72.0, 152.0)) {}
  [
    u'a big summit so that we can make decisions that everybody will work together. We all decided ' FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u"we'd put resources into the economy. Unfortunately, the Conservatives want to take these " FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u'resources out far too early and put thousands of jobs at risk. I would say this evening, David, ' FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u"you're a risk to the economy. Nick, you're a risk because of what you're saying on Iran and on " FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u'nuclear weapons to our security. Nick, you would leave us weak. David, you would leave us ' FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u'isolated in Europe.  I think these are the problems that these parties have got to face up to. We ' FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u'have a credible long-term plan for the future of Britain. ' FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
TextArea((24.0, 319.0), (212.0, 223.0)) {'type': 'INTERVIEWER'}
  [
    u'ADAM BOULTON: ' FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {'grabright': 300, 'type': 'INTERVIEWER'}
    u'Thank you, Mr Brown. David Cameron.  ' FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
TextArea((24.0, 562.0), (235.0, 408.0)) {'type': 'CAMERON'}
  [
    u'DAVID CAMERON: ' FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {'grabright': 300, 'type': 'CAMERON'}
    u"Well, I don't know about you, but I thought all that sounded slightly desperate and an attempt " FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u'to frighten people, instead of doing what I think we need to do in our country, which is to take ' FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u'and make a clean break from the last 13 years. To have new leadership, to take the country ' FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u'forward, to solve the problems that we have. I think the Conservatives are best-placed to offer ' FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u'that. If you vote Conservative, you know you can get fresh, new leadership, from a new team ' FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u"on May 7th, rather than being stuck with what we have now. You've heard in the debate today " FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u'some big differences set out between us, about how we believe you have to give more priority ' FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u'to keeping our country safe, keeping our borders secure, making sure we keep our defences ' FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u"strong. But also you've heard a lot of differences on values, how the family comes first for me, " FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u'how we need to do more to help those who actually do the right thing and want their ' FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u'Government behind them. We do face some difficult times in this country, but I still think we ' FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u"have incredible days ahead of us. We're a great country in so many different ways, with the " FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u'right leadership, with the right values, with a clean break from these 13 years of failure, we can ' FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u'achieve anything if we pull together and build the big society we all know we need to make our ' FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u'country a better place to live in.  ' FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
TextArea((24.0, 325.0), (420.0, 431.0)) {'type': 'INTERVIEWER'}
  [
    u'ADAM BOULTON: ' FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {'grabright': 300, 'type': 'INTERVIEWER'}
    u'Thank you, David Cameron. Nick Clegg.  ' FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
TextArea((24.0, 561.0), (443.0, 626.0)) {'type': 'CLEGG'}
  [
    u'NICK CLEGG: ' FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {'grabright': 300, 'type': 'CLEGG'}
    u'What I have tried to do tonight is to show if we do things differently, we can be a force for good ' FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u'in the world. We can lead, we can shape the world around us, not complain about the world ' FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u"around us. We have talked about a number of things this evening. We've talked about Europe, " FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u"Afghanistan, climate change, the Pope. We've talked about things closer to home as well, " FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u"immigration, MPs' expenses, pensions. I believe, on all those things, all those issues, we can " FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u"act differently. There's still some way to go before this election is decided, but I hope that " FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u"whether you're going to vote in the next few days by post, or make up your mind in the ballot " FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u'box on May 6th, you agree with me that something really exciting is beginning to happen. ' FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u'People are beginning to believe, beginning to hope that we can do something different this ' FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u'time. Of course there are people who will try to block change, of course there are people who ' FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u"are spreading fear to stop the change you want. I think they're wrong. I think if we do things " FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u"differently, if we stand up for the value's that have made our country great, then we can be " FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u'proud again, proud of greater fairness here at home, and proud also, of standing up for the ' FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u"things we believe in, in the world. We don't simply need to choose from the old choices of the " FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u"past, we don't need to repeat the mistakes of the past. Don't let anyone tell you this time it " FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u"can't be different. It can. " FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
TextArea((24.0, 563.0), (638.0, 718.0)) {'type': 'INTERVIEWER'}
  [
    u'ADAM BOULTON: ' FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {'grabright': 300, 'type': 'INTERVIEWER'}
    u" And that concludes this Sky News leaders' debate. Full reaction and analysis continues, of " FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u'course, now here live on Sky News. The third and final debate in this general election series ' FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u"will take place next week in the Midlands. After that, of course, it's up to you to cast your vote " FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u'on May 6th. Many thanks to you for watching, thanks to our questioners, to the our studio ' FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u'audience, and to the people of Bristol. And above all many thanks to our three leaders, the first ' FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u'ever to agree to debate live on television. Gordon Brown, David Cameron, and Nick Clegg who ' FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
  [
    u'I now invite to step forward and shake hands with each other. APPLAUSE  ' FontSpec(2 Times 7.0 #000000) {}
  ]
[
    [
        "INTERVIEWER", 
        "Good evening from the Arnolfini in Bristol and welcome to the Sky News leaders' debate, round two of the first ever televised prime ministerial debates in the UK. The three men who want to run the country after May 6th are here and raring to go, so please welcome David Cameron, Nick Clegg and Gordon Brown. APPLAUSE "
    ], 
    [
        "INTERVIEWER", 
        "The agreed theme for the first half of this debate is international affairs. Each leader will make a short opening statement before taking questions from the audience. In the second half tonight, we'll move on to general issues. Lots have been drawn to decide who goes first. We begin with the current Prime Minister and leader of the Labour Party, Gordon Brown. Mr Brown.  "
    ], 
    [
        "BROWN", 
        "This may have the feel of a TV popularity contest, but in truth, this is an election about Britain's future, a fight for your future, and for your jobs. If it's all about style and PR, count me out. If it's about the big decisions, if it's about judgment, it's delivering a better future for this country, I'm your man. Ahead are huge challenges, delivering the economic recovery in jobs, bringing our brave troops safely home from Afghanistan, keeping our streets free of terrorism, building alliances in Europe against nuclear weapons, against climate change, against poverty and to deal with our banks. Now, not everyone has the answers, but I say get the big decisions wrong and Britain's security and jobs are at risk. Get the big decisions right, and we can have a prosperous, fairer, greener and better Britain. Like me or not, I can deliver that plan. The way to do it is with a majority Labour government.  "
    ], 
    [
        "INTERVIEWER", 
        " Thank you, Mr Brown. Next, the leader of the Conservative Party, David Cameron.  "
    ], 
    [
        "CAMERON", 
        "Thank you. It's clear from last week's debate that the country wants change. But the question is, what sort of change and who's best placed to lead that change? If you vote Conservative, you will get a new team running the country from May 7th. And you won't be stuck with what you've got now. But real change comes from your values, and there, there are big differences between us. I believe that we need to do more to help families. They are the absolute bedrock of a strong society. I want government to be accountable. I want less waste, less bureaucracy. Stopping the jobs tax, but making sure we have good public services that you get good value for money for. As we're going to discuss tonight, I want us to keep our defences strong, I want to keep our borders secure and our country safe. But real change, real change comes not just from politicians, but from when we all recognise that we have responsibilities. We're all in this together, and that's how we will build the big and strong society I believe we need in our country. "
    ], 
    [
        "INTERVIEWER", 
        "Thank you, Mr Cameron. And finally in this round, Nick Clegg, the leader of the Liberal Democrats. "
    ], 
    [
        "CLEGG", 
        "I am so proud of the values that have made our country so great. Democracy, human rights, the rule of law. But the sad truth is that in recent years, our governments under the old parties have let those values down. We shouldn't have sent soldiers into battle without the right equipment. We shouldn't be facing allegations of complicity in torture, we shouldn't have invaded Iraq. So I want us to lead in the world. I want us to lead in Europe, not complain from the sidelines. I want us to lead in creating a world free of nuclear weapons. And I want us to lead on the biggest challenge of all, climate change. My family knows what British values really mean. My mother was freed by British troops from a prisoner of war camp. And I think, if we do things differently, we can be proud, once again, of the role we can play as a force for good in the world. "
    ], 
    [
        "INTERVIEWER", 
        "Thank you, Mr Clegg. Those are tonight's opening statements. Now it's time for the questions from the audience. The audience here is made up mainly of local voters from the south-west, some with allegiances, others yet to be persuaded. There will also be some questions in person from Sky News viewers who e-mailed us. Each leader has a uninterrupted minute to answer each question, followed by a second minute to deal with what their rivals have said. Then it's free debate time with no guaranteed time at the microphone. Now, our first question comes from Christopher Nelms, who's from Saltford, near Bristol. Mr Nelms.  "
    ], 
    [
        "AUDIENCE", 
        "Hello, I'm Chris Nelms, I work in the building trade. I can't see any advantage of us being in Europe. I think there's far too much interference politically and legally, and I just wonder what you intend to do to stop it?  "
    ], 
    [
        "INTERVIEWER", 
        " How are you going to tackle Europe, David Cameron?  "
    ], 
    [
        "CAMERON", 
        "Very directly, Christopher, I think we should be in Europe, because we're a trading nation, we're part of Europe, we want to co-operate and work with our allies in Europe to get things done. But I do agree with you that we have let too many powers go from Westminster to Brussels, we've  passed too much power over and we should take some of those powers back. I want us to be in Europe but not run by Europe. There will... you'll hear big differences between me and the other two parties. I don't want us to join the euro, I want I want us to keep the pound as our currency. I don't want us to give up the British rebate. I want to make sure we get value for money for what we put into Europe. I want to cut some of the bureaucracy, some of the rules, some of the regulations that I think drive business so mad. That's the agenda you'd get from a Conservative government in Europe. To those who say somehow this would be isolation, I say nonsense. President Sarkozy of France, he stands up for France in Europe. Angela Merkel in Germany, she stands up for Germany in Europe. I would do exactly the same for Europe.  "
    ], 
    [
        "INTERVIEWER", 
        " Thank you. Nick Clegg?  "
    ], 
    [
        "CLEGG", 
        "I actually worked for the man who was sent by Margaret Thatcher, would you believe it, to bat for Britain in Brussels. What I learned when I was there was this: the European Union is not perfect - of course not. This is a club that took 15 years to define \"chocolate\" in a chocolate directive. Anything that takes 15 years to define chocolate is not a model of democratic efficiency. What I also learned was this, that there are a whole load of things, whether we like it or not, whatever your views on Europe and the european Union, which we simply can't do on our own. We can't deal with international crime that touches and affects every single community in this country on our own. We can't deal with climate change on our own. The weather doesn't stop at the cliffs of Dover. We can't regulate these wretched banks that got us into so much in the first place which now sprawl across countries. I don't think the European Union is perfect. I want it reformed, that's why I want to lead in the European Union. But we're stronger together and we're weaker apart.  "
    ], 
    [
        "INTERVIEWER", 
        " Mr Brown?  "
    ], 
    [
        "BROWN", 
        "You know, there's three million reasons why we need to be part of the European Union, and they're called jobs. Three million jobs depend on our membership of the European Union. Half our trade is with the European Union. 750,000 businesses - I'm sorry it's not your business, raising the question about the building trade - but 750,000 businesses trade with Europe. The idea that we should again be isolated and on the margins and not in the mainstream of Europe would be a terrible, terrible mistake. Now, I worked with the European leaders through the global financial crisis. I had to persuade them that we had to restructure our banks and they had to restructure their banks. I had to persuade them they had to work with America in the G20, but when Europe and America works together, we are so much stronger. Stronger to deal with climate change, which is one much my priorities, stronger to deal with the economy, stronger to deal with international crime, stronger to deal with terrorism, let us never again be an empty chair in Europe. My fear is that David's policy would put us in that position.  "
    ], 
    [
        "INTERVIEWER", 
        " Thank you. David Cameron?  "
    ], 
    [
        "CAMERON", 
        "I understand why people like Christopher are frustrated about the European Union and some of the things that have happened. I think one of the reasons that people are so angry is that politicians at Westminster have given away powers to Brussels without asking us, the people, first. I think people felt particularly cheated when the European constitution came forward and we were told we were going to get a referendum and Gordon Brown and Labour stopped that from happening and Nick Clegg and the Liberal Democrats didn't vote with us to get that referendum. We should have had one. People feel cheated by that. As a result, one of the things I would do if I was your Prime Minister is straightaway pass a law through parliament that says if ever there's a future occasion when laws are being proposed to pass power from Westminster to Brussels, there will be a guarantee of a referendum held in our country. You send us to parliament to make decisions, make laws, discuss the issues, yes. You don't send us there to give away powers that belong to you. There should be a referendum guarantee if ever this happens again.  "
    ], 
    [
        "INTERVIEWER", 
        " Thank you. Mr Clegg.  "
    ], 
    [
        "CLEGG", 
